    <section id="home" class="active">
      <h2>Welcome to Nepali Festivals</h2>
      <p>This website celebrates Nepal's biggest and most loved festivals: <b>Dashain</b>, <b>Tihar</b>, and <b>Chhath</b>. Each of these festivals represents unity, joy, and devotion in Nepali culture.</p>
      <img src="images/Image05.jpg" alt="Home Image">
      </section>

    <section id="dashain">
      <h2>Dashain Festival</h2>
      <p>Dashain is the grandest festival in Nepal, symbolizing the victory of good over evil. It honors Goddess Durga, who defeated the demon Mahishasur. Families gather to receive tika and jamara from elders and enjoy delicious food.</p>
      <p>People fly kites, play cards, buy new clothes, and celebrate with joy throughout the country. It's a time for love, blessings, and family reunions.</p>
      <img src="images/Image01.png" alt="Dashain Image">
    </section>

    <section id="tihar">
      <h2>Tihar Festival</h2>
      <p>Tihar, also known as Deepawali, is the festival of lights and the second biggest festival in Nepal. It lasts five days, honoring animals like crows, dogs, and cows, and ends with Bhai Tika – celebrating the bond between brothers and sisters.</p>
      <p>Homes are decorated with diyos, candles, and lights. People sing Deusi-Bhailo and create colorful rangolis, filling the streets with joy and brightness.</p>
      <img src="images/Image04.jpg" alt="Tihar Image">
    </section>

    <section id="chhath">
      <h2>Chhath Festival</h2>
      <p>Chhath Puja is dedicated to the Sun God (Surya) and Chhathi Maiya. It is mainly celebrated in Nepal's Terai region. Devotees fast, stand in rivers, and offer prayers to the setting and rising sun for health and prosperity.</p>
      <p>This festival teaches purity, discipline, and deep gratitude to nature for giving life and energy to the world.</p>
      <img src="images/Image06.jpg" alt="Chhath Image">
    </section>

    <section id="experience">
      <h2>My Festival Experience</h2>
      <p>This year during Dashain, I visited my grandparents' home and received tika and jamara. During Tihar, I decorated our house with lights and diyos, and on Chhath, I watched devotees praying at the riverbank — it was truly beautiful.</p>
      <p>These festivals connect families, friends, and faith together. I love how everyone celebrates with happiness and togetherness.</p>
    </section>

